24 "§ 64-66. Divestiture procedure.
25 (a) Upon receipt of information that leads the Attorney General to believe that a violation
26 of G.S. 64-65 may have occurred, the Attorney General shall investigate the alleged violation
27 and may issue subpoenas requiring any of the following:
28 (1) Appearances of witnesses.
29 (2) Production of relevant records.
30 (3) Giving of relevant testimony.
31 (b) The Attorney General shall enforce a violation of G.S. 64-65 by commencing a
32 receivership proceeding under Article 38A of Chapter 1 of the General Statutes seeking the
33 appointment of a general receiver pursuant to G.S. 1-507.24(e1). The following apply to a
34 receivership proceeding initiated pursuant to this section:
35 (1) Proceeds of the sale shall be paid as follows:
36 a. The costs of the receivership and sale.
37 b. To secured parties, in their order of priority, except for liens which
38 under the terms of the sale are to remain on the property.
39 c. No proceeds shall be distributed from the receivership sale to the
40 prohibited foreign party. Any excess proceeds are forfeited and shall
41 be remitted to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with
42 G.S. 115C-457.2.
43 (2) At the receivership sale, any secured party shall be able to place a bid in an
44 amount that is not more than the amount owed plus any costs incurred to the
45 secured party as of the date of the sale, as established in the court order for the
46 sale of the property.
47 (3) Upon commencement of an action under this section, the Attorney General
48 shall file a notice of lis pendens as soon as practicable with the register of
49 deeds of the county or counties in which the real property is situated. Upon
50 the entry of an order for the sale of the property under this section, the
51 Attorney General shall record a copy of the order as soon as practicable in the
