8 RFP FOR STUDY OF UTILITY POLICIES TO INCREASE AFFORDABILITY OF
9 ELECTRIC RATES
10 SECTION 8. Recognizing the rising costs of utility service, the General Assembly
11 finds that an examination of various utility policies should be conducted to ensure these policies
12 are not exacerbating affordability issues for citizens of the State, including the 2050 goal for a
13 reduction in carbon dioxide (CO2) emitted in the State from electric generating facilities that
14 results in carbon neutrality, pursuant to G.S. 62-110.9. In addition to examining these existing
15 utility policies, the General Assembly finds that expert analysis should be performed to determine
16 the most effective approach to ensuring that costs of utility service to large load customers is not
17 borne by other residential, commercial, and industrial customers in North Carolina, including
18 appropriate terms for a large load tariff. The North Carolina Collaboratory (Collaboratory) shall
19 issue a request for proposals for a study to be conducted by an entity with nationally recognized
20 expertise in research and analysis of utility policy and rates to (i) ascertain the current impacts,
21 and projected impacts over the next 25 years, to residential, commercial, and industrial customer
22 bills from the 2050 carbon neutrality goal, and whether any changes to this policy or other
23 policies are advisable to enhance customer affordability and (ii) provide recommendations for
24 effective policies to prevent rate impacts from large load customers on other customer classes,
25 including requirements that large load customers generate a portion of their own power, as well
26 as curtailment policies for large load customers. The study shall adhere to the following time
27 line:
28 (1) The request for proposals (RFP) shall be issued on or before August 1, 2026.
29 (2) A contract to award the RFP shall be executed on or before November 1, 2026.
30 (3) The study shall be completed and submitted to the Joint Legislative
31 Commission on Energy Policy on or before May 1, 2027, in order to inform
32 the development of utility policy during the 2027 Regular Session.
33 The Utilities Commission and the Public Staff shall assist the (i) Collaboratory, as
34 needed, in the development of the RFP and the selection of a contractor and (ii) selected
35 contractor, in every permissible manner within the constraints of their respective authority, in the
36 conduct of the study.
37
38 EXPRESS PERMIT REVIEW FOR ENERGY PROJECTS
39 SECTION 9.(a) G.S. 143B-279.13 reads as rewritten:
40 "§ 143B-279.13. Express permit and certification reviews.
41 (a) The Department of Environmental Quality shall develop an express review program
42 to provide express permit and certification reviews in all of its regional offices. Participation in
43 the express review program is voluntary, and the program shall be supported by the fees
44 determined pursuant to subsection (b) of this section. The Department of Environmental Quality
45 shall determine the project applications to review under the express review program from those
46 who request to participate in the program. The express review program may be applied to any
47 one or all of the permits, approvals, or certifications in the following programs: the erosion and
48 sedimentation control program, the coastal management program, and the water quality
49 programs, including water quality certifications and stormwater management. The express
50 review program shall focus on the following permits or certifications:
