5 (3) Water quality certification under Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General
6 Statutes.
7 (4) Erosion and sedimentation control permits under Article 4 of Chapter 113A
8 of the General Statutes.
9 (5) Permits under the Coastal Area Management Act (CAMA), Part 4 of Article
10 7 of Chapter 113A of the General Statutes.
11 (a1) The Department of Environmental Quality shall have the authority to create express
12 permitting options for programs in addition to those listed in subsection (a) of this section where
13 it deems there to be a need or where it determines an express permitting option would create
14 greater efficiencies for the permitting process.
15 (a2) The Department of Environmental Quality shall create an express review program for
16 all permits, authorizations, and certifications required from the Department for projects involving
17 the generation, distribution, or transmission of energy or fuel, including natural gas, diesel,
18 petroleum, or electricity. Participation in the express review program is voluntary.
19 (b) The Department of Environmental Quality shall set the fees for express application
20 review under the express review program at a level sufficient to cover all program expenses.
21 Notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D, the maximum permit application fee to be charged under
22 subsection (a) of this section for the express review of a project application requiring all of the
23 permits under subdivisions (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section shall not exceed five
24 thousand eight hundred eight dollars ($5,808). Notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D, the maximum
25 permit application fee to be charged for the express review of a project application requiring all
26 of the permits under subdivisions (1) through (4) of subsection (a) of this section shall not exceed
27 four thousand seven hundred fifty-two dollars ($4,752). Notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D, the
28 maximum permit application fee charged for the express review of a project application for any
29 other combination of permits under subdivisions (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section
30 shall not exceed four thousand two hundred twenty-four dollars ($4,224). As set forth in
31 subsection (a1) of this section, express review of a project application involving additional
32 permits or certifications issued by the Department of Environmental Quality other than those
33 under subdivisions (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section may be allowed by the
34 Department, and, notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D or any other statute or rule that sets a permit
35 fee, the maximum permit application fee charged for the express review of a project application
36 that includes a permit, approval, or certification designated for express review under subsection
37 (a1) of this section shall not exceed four thousand two hundred twenty-four dollars ($4,224), plus
38 one hundred fifty percent (150%) of the fee that would otherwise apply by statute or rule for that
39 particular permit, approval, or certification. Additional fees, not to exceed fifty percent (50%) of
40 the original permit application fee under this section, may be charged for subsequent reviews due
41 to the insufficiency of the permit applications. The Department of Environmental Quality may
42 establish the procedure by which the amount of the fees under this subsection is determined, and
43 the fees and procedures are not rules under G.S. 150B-2(8a) for the express review program
44 under this section."
45 SECTION 9.(b) G.S. 143B-279.20 reads as rewritten:
46 "§ 143B-279.20. Report on Department activity to process applications for permits
47 required for natural gas pipelines and gas-fired electric generation facilities.
48 The Department of Environmental Quality shall report on any applications received for
49 permits permits, authorizations, or certifications required for siting or operation of natural gas
50 pipelines and gas-fired electric generation facilities within the State, and activities of the
51 Department to process such applications, including tracking of processing times. The report shall
Page 10 Senate Bill 730-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 also include information on all activities under the express review program required pursuant to
2 G.S. 143B-279.13(a2). The processing time tracked shall include (i) the total processing time
3 from when an initial permit application is received to issuance or denial of the permit and (ii) the
4 processing time from when a complete permit application is received to issuance or denial of the
5 permit. The Department shall report quarterly to the Joint Legislative Commission on Energy
6 Policy pursuant to this section."
7 SECTION 9.(c) Within 30 days of the date this section becomes law, the Department
8 shall notify applicants for all entities with pending applications for permits, authorizations, and
9 certifications required from the Department for projects involving the generation, distribution, or
10 transmission of energy or fuel, including natural gas, diesel, petroleum, or electricity, of the
11 express review program enacted by subsection (b) of this section, and shall inform the applicants
12 of the ability to process pending applications through the program upon payment of the applicable
13 fee pursuant to G.S. 143B-279.13(b).
14 SECTION 9.(d) This section is effective when it becomes law and applies to
15 applications for permits, authorizations, and certifications pending on or submitted after that date.
16
17 REQUIRE DEVELOPMENT OF NUCLEAR RESOURCES PRIOR TO RETIREMENT
18 OF BASELOAD FACILITIES OR FACILITIES WITH DISPATCHABLE ELECTRIC
19 GENERATION ABOVE 100 MW TO ENSURE ADEQUACY OF GRID
20 SECTION 10. G.S. 62-110.9(4) reads as rewritten:
21 "(4) Retain discretion to determine optimal timing and generation and
22 resource-mix to achieve the least cost path to compliance with the authorized
23 carbon reduction goal, including discretion in achieving the authorized carbon
24 reduction goal by the date specified in order to allow for implementation of
25 solutions that would have a more significant and material impact on carbon
26 reduction; provided, however, the Commission shall not exceed the date
27 specified to achieve the authorized carbon reduction goal by more than two
28 years, except in the event the Commission authorizes construction of a nuclear
29 facility or wind energy facility that would require additional time for
30 completion due to technical, legal, logistical, or other factors beyond the
31 control of the electric public utility, or in the event necessary to maintain the
32 adequacy and reliability of the existing grid. In making such determinations,
33 the Utilities Commission shall receive and consider stakeholder input. The
34 Commission shall not authorize retirement of baseload facilities or facilities
35 with dispatchable electric generation above 100 MW until such time as a
36 certificate of public convenience and necessity has been issued to an electric
37 public utility for construction of one nuclear facility with a generating capacity
38 of at least 1,000 MW to ensure the adequacy of baseload and dispatchable
39 generation from a clean energy resource."
40
41 PART III. MISCELLANEOUS
42
43 COOLING-OFF PERIOD FOR UTILITIES COMMISSIONERS AND STAFF
44 SECTION 11.(a) Article 15 of Chapter 62 of the General Statutes is amended by
45 adding a new section to read:
46 "§ 62-327A. Post-employment restrictions on members and employees of Commission.
47 (a) Cooling-Off Period. ‒ It shall be unlawful for any former commissioner or employee
48 of the Commission to make, with the intent to influence on behalf of an employer or client, any
49 communication to or appearance before the Commission within a period of six months following
50 the termination of his or her service or employment with the Commission.
51 (b) Penalty. ‒ A violation of this section is a Class 3 misdemeanor."
Senate Bill 730-Fifth Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 11.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
2 offenses committed on or after that date.
